04372nam a22007215i 9780271094632DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710946327 a10.1515/97802710946322doi  a(DE-B1597)677953  a(OCoLC)1411045745  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aND1322.2b.J37 2023eb 7aART0150802bisacsh04a757.0946/090312221 aJasienski, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPraying to Portraits :bAudience, Identity, and the Inquisition in the Early Modern Hispanic World /cAdam Jasienski. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Portraits and Sacred Images in Early Modernity -- tChapter 1 Sacrificing the Self -- tChapter 2 True Portraits, Lying Portraits -- tChapter 3 Repainting Portraits -- tPortraits as Sacred Images -- tConclusion: The Life Histories of Sacred Portraits and the History of Sacred Portraiture -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Praying to Portraits, art historian Adam Jasienski examines the history, meaning, and cultural significance of a crucial image type in the early modern Hispanic world: the sacred portrait. Across early modern Spain and Latin America, people prayed to portraits. They prayed to “true” effigies of saints, to simple portraits that were repainted as devotional objects, and even to images of living sitters depicted as holy figures. Jasienski places these difficult-to-classify image types within their historical context. He shows that rather than being harbingers of secular modernity and autonomous selfhood, portraits were privileged sites for mediating an individual’s relationship to the divine. Using Inquisition records, hagiographies, art-theoretical treatises, poems, and plays, Jasienski convincingly demonstrates that portraiture was at the very center of broader debates about the status of images in Spain and its colonies.Highly original and persuasive, Praying to Portraits profoundly revises our understanding of early modern portraiture. It will intrigue art historians across geographical boundaries, and it will also find an audience among scholars of architecture, history, and religion in the early modern Hispanic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian art and symbolismzLatin Americay16th century. 0aChristian art and symbolismzLatin Americay17th century. 0aChristian art and symbolismzSpainy16th century. 0aChristian art and symbolismzSpainy17th century. 0aPortrait painting, Latin Americany16th century. 0aPortrait painting, Latin Americany17th century. 0aPortrait painting, Spanishy16th century. 0aPortrait painting, Spanishy17th century. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aBaroque.  aColonial Latin America.  aGolden Age.  aHispanic.  aInquisition.  aMexico.  aPortrait.  aRenaissance.  aSpain.  aearly modern.  aportraiture.  areligious art.  aseventeenth century.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271094632?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271094632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271094632/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles